Developer Integration Playground (MVP) - System Design & Implementation Prompt

Objective

Design and implement an MVP of a Developer Integration Playground for local integration and end-to-end testing of Spring Boot microservices.

This is NOT a production platform. It is an internal developer productivity tool that allows developers to spin up complete integration environments with minimal effort.

The focus is simplicity, extensibility and rapid development.

⸻

Core Problem

A typical Spring Boot service depends on:

* Multiple external REST APIs
* Kafka
* Databases
* Redis
* File systems
* Other Spring Boot services

Developers spend significant time:

* configuring local environments
* starting dependencies
* creating test data
* mocking APIs
* inspecting Kafka topics
* checking database changes
* switching between IntelliJ, Postman, Kafka UI, Docker, logs and database tools

The playground should consolidate these activities into a single tool.

⸻

Important Constraints

DO NOT modify existing Spring Boot applications.

No code changes.

No additional dependencies.

No AOP.

No Java Agent.

No OpenTelemetry requirement.

No framework changes.

The playground must work with existing applications exactly as they are.

⸻

High-Level Concept

The Playground acts as an orchestrator, not part of the application.

Responsibilities:

* provision infrastructure
* generate runtime configuration
* launch services
* configure mock APIs
* manage embedded Kafka
* manage databases
* provide unified visibility

Applications simply consume the generated configuration.

⸻

